&nbsp;
A controversy began after the 2005 elections when reformist leader Mehdi Karroubi publicly asked Khamenei to "avoid Mojtaba interference" in the electoral process. A controversy that has since had a reflection on public opinion; during the protests that have cyclically inflamed since 2009 the Iranian squares, slogans and songs have never been missing against Mojtaba.> To the polemics the organ in charge of choosing the Supreme Guide, the Assembly of Experts, responded ensuring that to be decisive will be "merit and qualifications". Double-cut words, which do not extrude Mojtaba, indeed define its possible election as a result of a democratic election. Prospect even more dangerous, because it would clean up the rise of Mojtaba from those charges of hereditary charge that the regime wants to avoid at all costs, because it would bring Iran back to the time of the Pahlavi dynasty and the Shah monarchy: the dictatorship that inspired the revolution and the birth of the Islamic Republic.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Iran has come from the elections that have determined the composition of the new Parliament and the Assembly of Experts, the organ responsible for choosing the successor of Khamenei. Elections characterized by very little turnout to the urns (about 40%) and the victory of ultra-conservative components, whose rise was favored by censorship of all the reformist elements that had submitted their candidacy. Among these Hassan Rouhani, one of the possible successors of Khamenei, at least on the card, whose election now appears increasingly unlikely. The last elections are in fact served in Khamenei to ensure control over the Assembly of Experts and, consequently, on its succession. President Ebrahim Raisi, who will try to consolidate his position in the next few months, remains the candidate.
