&nbsp;
The American secretary of state Antony Blinken, in the meantime, goes to Saudi Arabia today in an attempt to reach a truce in the war between Israel and the Hamas Palestinian movement. Tomorrow the American representative will be in Egypt, a country bordering the Gaza Strip which is participating in mediation efforts for a ceasefire in the Palestinian territories. Blinken arrives in the Middle East in the middle of a new cycle of talks mediated by Qatar, after the failure of an attempt to reach a ceasefire in the Gaza Strip for the beginning of the Muslim sacred month of Ramadan. Almost six months after the war, the United States urged their ally Israel to increase humanitarian aid in Gaza. Yesterday, the American secretary underlined that the entire population of Gaza suffers from "gravious levels of serious food insecurity". Another area of concern for the United States, the UN and humanitarian groups is the city of Rafah, at the southern end of the Gaza Strip. Blinken's visit to the Middle East is part of the pressures exerted by the U.S. on Israel to avoid the large-scale offensive in Rafah and allow greater access to humanitarian aid. The Biden administration is considering several alternatives to an Israeli invasion of Rafah and will propose them to the high-level Israeli delegation, led by Defense Minister Gallant, who will visit Washington next week. This evening the Israeli prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, will speak to the Gop senators of the U.S. Congress to convince them of the opportunity to carry out the operation. &nbsp;

